headline: Tech Weekly: Nvidia gets China nod, eye-catching robots
summary: STORY: Nvidia gets a Chinese bonus but with a price... to eye-catching robots...This is Tech Weekly.:: Tech WeeklyNvidia can sell its second-best AI chips to China, but with a price.U.S. President Donald Trump confirmed Washington will allow the sale of H200 processors but collect a 25% fee on such sales.It's higher than the 15% levy suggested in August.The White House said it will be collected as an import tax from Taiwan, where the chips are made, before they undergo U.S. security checks and head to China.Australia is on course to ban under 16s from using social media.It would make it the first country to bring in a minimum age for social media use.And could lead to fines of around $33 million if 10 of the biggest platforms, including Meta and TikTok, don't follow along.Major tech firms and free speech advocates have criticized the move, but parents and child advocates have praised it. China's LandSpace rocket failed to complete its reusable rocket test.The firm had hoped to become the third company after SpaceX and Blue Origin to successfully test a reusable spacecraft.State media said the Zhuque-3 rocket couldn't complete a controlled landing following an initial launch.The latest advances in robotic technology were on show in Japan at the International Robot Exhibition.Some were able to show their rescue capabilities during disasters,While others danced and served up drinks.Some like Kawasaki Corporation's Kaleido 9 robot could one day be used in disaster areas where human access is difficult.And India is reviewing a proposal about greater phone-location surveillance.That's according to documents, emails and five sources.The pitch is from the telecom industry to force smartphone firms to enable satellite location tracking.Tech majors, including Apple, Google and Samsung, have all opposed the move due to privacy concerns.

raw.headline: Tech Weekly: Nvidia gets China nod, eye-catching robots
raw.summary: STORY: Nvidia gets a Chinese bonus but with a price... to eye-catching robots...This is Tech Weekly.:: Tech WeeklyNvidia can sell its second-best AI chips to China, but with a price.U.S. President Donald Trump confirmed Washington will allow the sale of H200 processors but collect a 25% fee on such sales.It's higher than the 15% levy suggested in August.The White House said it will be collected as an import tax from Taiwan, where the chips are made, before they undergo U.S. security checks and head to China.Australia is on course to ban under 16s from using social media.It would make it the first country to bring in a minimum age for social media use.And could lead to fines of around $33 million if 10 of the biggest platforms, including Meta and TikTok, don't follow along.Major tech firms and free speech advocates have criticized the move, but parents and child advocates have praised it. China's LandSpace rocket failed to complete its reusable rocket test.The firm had hoped to become the third company after SpaceX and Blue Origin to successfully test a reusable spacecraft.State media said the Zhuque-3 rocket couldn't complete a controlled landing following an initial launch.The latest advances in robotic technology were on show in Japan at the International Robot Exhibition.Some were able to show their rescue capabilities during disasters,While others danced and served up drinks.Some like Kawasaki Corporation's Kaleido 9 robot could one day be used in disaster areas where human access is difficult.And India is reviewing a proposal about greater phone-location surveillance.That's according to documents, emails and five sources.The pitch is from the telecom industry to force smartphone firms to enable satellite location tracking.Tech majors, including Apple, Google and Samsung, have all opposed the move due to privacy concerns.
